A Republican strategy to counter the re-election of Obama
Republicans' leaders justify their policies with the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter to be a myth by affirming that election fraud in the US is less frequent than the number of people killed by lightning.
The Republicans' lawyers have, by the way, recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the US in 10 years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the US.
In contrast to Canada, the US states are responsible for the conduct of the elections in the individual states.
In this sense, since 2009, the majority of American governments have announced new laws that have made the procedure for registration or the first step more difficult.
This phenomenon has become more important after the November 2010 elections, where 675 new Republican representatives have been registered in 26 countries.
As a result, 180 draft laws were introduced in 2011 alone, which restrict the exercise of the right to vote in 41 countries.
The new electoral laws require voters to present a photo card and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce the periods of early voting, invalidate the right to register as a electorate on the day of the election, and give citizens the right to vote for which a court act is in place.
Before the 2006 elections, no US state asked the voters to show a photo card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a claim.
In 2008, the Supreme Court of the United States confirmed the constitutional nature of the Indiana Act.
The Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other countries.
Over the last two years, they have promoted draft laws in 34 states that force voters to show a photo card.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, US citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, i.e. 21 million persons entitled to vote, do not have a photo card issued by a government authority in their country.
In addition, five million new voters do not have such an ID in 2012.
However, more than a hundred dollars are often to be paid to get the required ID.
The new restrictions are disproportionately affected by young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of Afro-Americans, 15% of people with an income of less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 and 20% of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the necessary photo ID.
This is much more than that.
The students who are considered to be voters who give their votes more for democratic candidates are not allowed in several countries to use their photo card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting associations to choose more for the Republican side to use the cards issued by these associations for elections.
Before 2004, no state required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first state to introduce such a claim.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws that require the voters to prove their US citizenship.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the Hispanic votes.
It is clear that two out of three Hispanic voters who prefer democratic parties.
In addition, in 2011, Republican legislators in eight states have promoted laws that abolished the registration of voters on election day.
In addition, you have limited the right of individuals and groups to help those voters who wish to register.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, the electoral registration campaigns in the 2004 general elections have helped to register about 10 million citizens.
The measures adopted since 2009 have reduced the proportion of new voters in 2010 by 17% compared to 2006.
In addition, the Republican legislators in five other states have adopted laws aimed at reducing the period for early voting.
For example, in the 2008 general elections in Florida, 33% of the voters who have voted in advance were Afro-Americans, although they represent only 13% of the voters of the state.
The same applies to the Hispanic population.
The latter represented only 11% of the voters, but 24% of the citizens who voted in advance.
By contrast, the white people, who represented 76% of the voters, represented only 46% of the voters who voted in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws that restrict the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were blocked by the vetos of democratic governors.
The US Advocate General has intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They could partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring the display of a photo card.
However, the new rules introduced in 2012 will undoubtedly make the exercise of the right to vote more difficult.
The democratic critics denounce the party-political nature of the adopted laws and see them as a clear objective of influencing the results in the countries that are the key to 2012.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that those states that have passed these laws are 171 out of the 270 votes required by the Electoral Board to win the Presidency.
It is too early to confirm with certainty that these amendments to the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on turnout.
In this sense, these measures are partly undermining the democratic system of the US.
