The Higgs-Boson Analyses
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs-Boson has caused some concern last summer, and for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism that is responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it is the last particle whose existence has been predicted, but has not yet been observed empirically, by the standard model - our best or "least wrong" explanation of nature and the behaviour of matter.
But for the physicists it is not yet completely certain that this is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs Boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be fully sure of it.
Let us still assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be a low risk of being wrong, and let us look at what it is.
There is an inevitable law in this world that causes two objects to not be present at the same time in the same place.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try too hard as you will hurt yourself.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law also applies to it: the Pauli principle of exclusion, which says that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state," with this "state" largely consisting of some of their properties.
From this point on, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In a corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione and are kind to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, a bad band of anarchists, to whom nothing is holy - in any case not this principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons, according to the website The Particle Adventure, are divided into two groups from the Berkeley laboratories (which is by the way absolutely amazing): the mesons that we are not going to treat here and the "force particles" through which the great forces of nature are spreading and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
It must be stressed here, however, that these bosons are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" that is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "disturbed" right at this place, in about like a pebble stone that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbance" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force."
More stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "disturbed" so that this boson is shown.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen must reach very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond, whose surface could only be feared by a very large rock.
This is why a huge particle accelerator like CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a circumference of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep on the fridge by itself.
And equally, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (like the photon by the way) do not have a mass.
What can all these research be "good" for now, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, they are used to check the standard model (SM), and they also allow the physicists to examine all the differences between the observations and the forecasts of the SM.
There are, by the way, numerous physicists who are hopeful that such differences will be found, as the least difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has major shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for gravity (ups!) and dark matter, which is about 80% of the matter of the universe (again up!).
However, such differences have not yet been found at CERN.
Effects
The impact of this research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there was no research.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who developed the first permanent laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962 - already told us that the laser was in the beginning rather than a "laboratory play."
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also result from all the instruments that surround research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in the optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, this sensor today serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and has presented it with the Nobel Prize in Physics in 2009.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you really can never know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...
With her Committee on Dying in Dignity, Quebec has recently discussed the sensitive issue of the end of life.
The debate must be resumed shortly, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, much remains to be done in this important area.
Le Devoir has tried to take a closer look at this.
A few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer, which consumed him, had given him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I managed seven years," he said, half-hearted, lying in his bed in the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for that," he says.
The disease is doing its job: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped with the food.
He is even able to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medication, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"In the course of our lives we learn that a man is peeing standing up," says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois home.
To return to the childhood phase is an unacceptable humiliation for certain people.
"This depends on the ability of the person to take a step back," he notes.
In the opinion of several people who work in palliative care, great events take place in the midst of these steps.
The patients who are introduced to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, the doctors and nurses who take care of them will no longer be taken care of with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation."
But the disease really made me meet my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I have no more wishes in life," she says, before she accepts that she is being put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days she still expects a last visit of her son, who comes from Italy.
In the Victor-Gadbois home you can offer a group of volunteers and help with the food intake.
Palliative care is used when there are no other options.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec, there is a bed for palliative care on a population of 11,700.
That is very little, considering that one day we will all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying person is given a mouth care with brandy or pepsi as desired.
Diabetics no longer need to control their blood sugar level.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning, his son will drink the beer at the foot of the deceased.
"We help family members and patients alike," reports caretaker Nathalie Savard.
There's no day at the Victor-Gadbois home like the other.
In addition to an old man of 93 years, who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while he is attacked in his honor, a young man of 36 years, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
"For six months, three to five beds have always been filled with cancer patients less than 45 years of age," says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois' home come from their home, 47% come from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, that is to say, to a care that is intended to alleviate the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, both at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Victor-Gadbois home and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Greater Montreal area, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great inadequacy in the health care of Quebecs that makes it possible for several doctors specialized in palliative care to look forward to the adoption of a law on the regulation of death aid and assisted suicide with concern.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent people of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quabec health system is not powerful enough to ensure that all have the right to high-quality palliative care before being accepted to go to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency room for 14 days with a lot of pain without taking measures to relieve her.
I fear that patients will only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologues treat their patients, despite worst forecasts, until the last day.
The chances of Hélène Richard's survival were already minimal when she stopped a hard chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry that I was giving up the fight, she said.
But she told me I was finished!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the care staff for not accepting this wish after their pain has been alleviated by a palliative care team.
However, it must be clearly stated that palliative care is not omnipotent in pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of the palliative care company of the home palliative care of the Greater Montreal area, 8% of patients do not respond to pain treatment.
At the very end of life, the doctors often use the terminal sedation, which is to put the patient to sleep either sporadically or permanently until the time of his death.
We can no longer pretend that we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be more and more likely to use this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not alleviated all say the same sentence, "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean, "I want you to put me down," but "I want my pain to be alleviated."
