In fact, the Bitcoin, created by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but can be converted into dollars, euro, etc.) and a protocol for the safe exchange, such as BitTorrent, which allows the direct exchange of files.
With 15,000 computers on the network, about 200,000 transactions have already been recorded.
A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or as a means of payment.
After the price of Bitcoin had reached a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, it fell five months later to 2 dollars before recovering to about 10 dollars today (the rates are listed on the website bitcoin charts.com).
Nothing particularly impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success," "in competition with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to the traditional currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as the "credits" used to move forward in a video game that can be won or bought by games (and sometimes exchanged back).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, each time the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority.
With Bitcoin all network nodes are at the same time depositors of the accounting book, auditors, money issuers, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way the network can check the authenticity of the transaction.
The content of the file also makes it possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the public accounts' accounting book spread throughout the network.
The decisive step is to enter this new transaction in this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that is started on the computers, with the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker, having the privilege of adding this additional line.
It is a disassembly of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is "hacked."
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
When this number is found, the other nodes can easily check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay for fraud twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other would remain unlinked, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task gets 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be divided to a hundredth of a million, which leaves a certain margin...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
"The weak point used does not concern the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced a payment that is a company for payment with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB shall also report on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also has these shortcomings.
Important actors such as Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel have analysed the accounting book and showed that almost 80% of the bitcoins are out of circulation.
In November a "mega-sales" was launched.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," is Jon Holmquist, who works for the company Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
The Paytunia system is a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by the dealers and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to provide an address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend in which hierarchical systems are reconsidered in favour of more horizontal systems.
"It will take some time to get Bitcoin through, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB, by the way, in its report provides for a reassessment of the various risks now considered to be high in the event of the success of this currency.
