A constitution with the crowbar in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains divided more than ever in relation to the constitutional declaration, which temporarily gives it unlimited authority, it has decided to put everything on one card.
To the surprise of everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constitutional Assembly would adopt its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had granted this Assembly two additional months to complete his work.
Egypt has now been based on a provisional text, which has been amended several times for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal confusion.
This new initiative has only provided for an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the President remains in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step right with his feet."
His supporters are assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period, which forces the brothers to renounce their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians by section.
It is also a way for the President to find his public and democratic legitimacy again, while the protest is raging throughout the country.
After affirming in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
In the case of the Egyptian people, with this use of an overhasty vote, an ultimatum is given: "Either you vote for my draft or I keep the unlimited power of authority," the latter should probably end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 most of the Islamist members of this constitutional assembly passed the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have not responded to the request.
They have turned away just before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, as they believe that they have not been able to make their views known.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted in the same way.
In order to achieve the quorum, 11 people, alternate members, were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that most of the articles have been adopted unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it amusing that the only difference of opinion of the day was expressed in the time of prayer, as some members of the panel felt that the commuting clock of the constitutional assembly was not exactly going.
The text, which was adopted last night, is made up of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, remains the same as that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law."
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope to replace "the principles" with "the rules," which would have made it possible to apply more strictly.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is proof of their good will and respect for the other members of Egyptian society.
"Objection" is the answer to the liberals who only consider this a propaganda strike.
They say that the Constitution is being Islamised by other articles.
They are particularly concerned with Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory role, in particular as regards the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to the Egyptian specialist Sophie Pimier, this is worrying because "the people who are asked to give an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy. "
The concerns of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the present one.
"At the moment, there is no concrete religious commitment.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most of the lawyers who have worked on this text are not ulema, but academics who have been partly trained in the French system, "says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
He admitted, however, that "there may be a ambiguity in relation to Article 220, since the terms used are derived from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, it refers to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, An. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil judges are competent to decide. "
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised for the far-reaching powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the request of the military, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights associations have called for.
The latter also share their concerns about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The situation of blasphemy is maintained and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no more article refers to the protection of women, underlines Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In their opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian President had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The proponents of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy sites, the world's navel and a sea of brine
The Promised Land unites in itself the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and an unspoiled nature.
AIF gives you the five most important reasons for visiting Israel.
Bow before the holy places
Visit the river Jordan where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that all who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus did his wonders: the conversion of water into wine at a wedding party, the walking on the water, the stalling of the sea storm and the fishing.
It was here that Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Believers here commit the way of suffering or the way of the cross of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on the mountain Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the grave of Jesus are located.
This is the Christian view of the world's navel, which symbolizes the salvation of humanity.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem is located in the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree from which the Cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the clavings, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
Traditionally, people of different faiths leave a note of wishes there, which then come into being.
Take a trip to the height
The ruins of the Masada Fortress form the remains of the secret hiding place of enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in the year 25 AD.
They are located on a rock wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins of their own power.
All the others bring an airtrack to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters above sea level is the famous ski resort Hermon, in which it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can get there with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an old legend, pagan gods lived on the mountain summit.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be visited.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There are old Qumranmanuscripts or scrolls from the Dead Sea found in rock caves in the Judean Desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
The collection of works by the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited there.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no museum guides or souvenir shops there.
The entrance is free and donations are generally rejected.
The fifth museum, the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most shocking chapters of history.
The most gripping section is the monument for the children, which was built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is complete darkness.
Stars are sparing.
And the names of the Jewish children and the countries in which they died will be heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three most important recreational areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, delfinariums and oceanariums.
In the Red Sea, the water temperature is not below 21 ° C and the air is warm up to 23 ° C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and is bathed all year round.
By the way, this unusual sea, with a location of 417 meters below sea level, is the lowest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries non-swimmers on the surface without any problems.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt sole) and healing sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of strained nerves.
Touch the secrets of antiquity
These secrets are in the old town of Tel Aviv, the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city the famous sea road, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia, was run.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda with which he had a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to stroll through the narrow streets, which are named after the signs of the zodiac.
Fortuna is to be found in the legend of all those who touch the walls in the alley with their zodiac sign.
In Jaffa you can meet newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at the photo gallery.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusaders.
In the Roman era, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and the residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Watch list for tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of the Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the journey is rather not taken in euro, but in dollars, which can be easily changed to shekel (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekel).
In the city you are mostly by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a fast-track and in Haifa the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the subtown with the upper city.
In fact, it's an underground funicular.
A journey within the city costs 6 shekels, regardless of the means of transport, which is enough for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated on Saturdays in Israel.
From Friday evening to Saturday's sunset, markets and shops are closed and public transport is resting.
And on Sunday morning, the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and restaurants, only kosher food is served, which excludes pork, sea products, fish without scales and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice of different dishes with mutton and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, various sauces, fried balls of pureed beans and peas (falafel), as well as fruit and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-nourished cats that walk through the streets in a comfortable and uneasy way.
In the evening you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
The cats like busy places and don't say no to treats.
A rental car costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the brand.
The insurance costs an additional 15 dollars a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
On average, tickets for museums cost 30 shekels.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of the adventurers and those looking for a rest came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the Promised Land, an increase of 51% compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the visa waiver on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While MEPs and civil rights activists are discussing the benefits of the law on binding language tests for migrants, criminals are already acting with fake certificates.
Every year, 13 million host workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities in Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families that remain in their home country.
On 1 December, a law came into force, according to which every labour migrant must take a test that certifies knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this scheme only applies to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the local housing industry and in the retail sector.
However, over time, according to the Federal Migration Authority, the tests will become a duty for all host workers in the future.
It is necessary to put not only language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the foundations of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the receipt and the extension of the work permit.
The exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
This law also excludes persons who received their certificates and diplomas before the USSR was destroyed in 1991.
Sense, problem and protection of rights
The whole of the examination posts will be under the aegis of the Pushkin Institute for the Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can take the tests in all cities and more than 160 appropriate centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
However, before the entry into force of the law in the press several times asked the following question: what is the point of the whole thing?
What changes does the requirement to have language skills bring, both for the Russians and for the host workers?
In particular, I would like to say that it is a question of reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about the protection of the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelew, head of the Federal Migration Authority's Representation in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before their departure.
Only organised recruitment will 90% solve the problems of foreign workers.
There are problems with migrants without a job, education, language skills and medical advice.
Sebelev is convinced that a future migrant without language knowledge will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who, under the pretext of help, put him in a dark, narrow barrack, where he will stay with dozens of his same months without food and documents and work 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home country, the One is promised to you, and on arrival you will be cheated, your passports will be taken off and will not receive the promised pay," confirmed the head of the labour migration office of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't be shy, boss!
However, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to make their money in Russia admit that they are not only not able to master the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, but rather the evil: only a few Turkmen, Uzbeks and Tajiks can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone buy them decent clothes, shoes and school stuff.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It's difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect in relation to the law.
The test must be carried out only by migrants with legal status.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome" or "Access prohibited for unauthorized persons"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to get official status in Russia.
The reason is bureaucratic barriers and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The Russian police know that most of our documents are fake and we are not registered, and this will result in cases of blackmail.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," says the Tajike Umed Huschkadamov to journalists.
"Just don't be afraid of costs for false papers"
The day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of the migrants could be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been confiscated by the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get it for nothing: any migrant who hoped to be able to save the tests in this way paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily bought, is both public officials and civil rights activists agree.
For the moment, the public authorities can only promise that they will have time for a basic language course, which will fall through the test the first time.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where active communication with people is not necessary.
Interior Ministry ignores illegal arms market
The share of legal weapons in crime is very low
The Russian Ministry of the Interior is planning to strengthen the arms law for private arms owners.
In doing so, the authorities respond to recent events: injured in shooting at weddings and seven dead in the amocle of the Moscow lawyer Dmitri Winogradov.
The police want to ban the use of non-lethal weapons in public and increase the age for possession of firearms from 18 to 21 years.
The proposal was supported by the president of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Jarovaya, and promised that the amendments to the arms law will be submitted to the Duma shortly.
Not all are satisfied that the Russian authorities want to fight the problems by "attracting the screws."
An open letter was published on the Internet, the authors of which - representatives of various arms associations - call on the authorities to refrain from "senseless smears."
The percentage of the crimes with registered weapons is very low, said the criminal lawyer, Vasilij Lesnikov, the Russian service of the BBC.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of the Interior, 142 crimes involving the use of the registered weapons were committed in 2012 over the course of six months, while a total of 1,168 thousand crimes were reported for the same period.
The authors of the open letter are convinced that a tightening of the law for private arms owners will not prevent criminals from using the black market.
At the moment, according to the authors in Moscow, you can find any weapon for little money.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of the Interior stresses that the proliferation of illegal weapons is under control.
Suppliers: from the factories to the officers
The weapons reach the black market via several channels.
There are five such main channels, a former Colonel Viktor Baranez, who worked for ten years in the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a website that accepts arms orders
The first channel is the army or the military, i.e. weapons stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
"The weapons were stolen by both the Russian officers and the Caucasians themselves," says Baranez.
On the second channel, there are illegal weapons that are stolen by criminals.
Baranez explains that these include weapons stolen from both the police arms chambers and directly from law enforcement staff.
Other illegally sold weapons come from military weapons camps.
There were often explosions in many military camps.
"There is evidence that some cases were arson to cover up the lack of weapons," says the former military member.
According to Baranez, the arms manufacturers also contribute to the black market.
"Today, there are countless private arms factories that do not stand up to international competition and that is why the expert reports that the weapons are being smeared under the black market, for example in Moscow.
Another channel of the black market is smuggling.
Especially many pistols and rifles come from poor countries like Kyrgyzstan.
"There is a production of its own, sometimes artisanal, as well as a mafia that organises the smuggling," explains the former military member.
Where did the guns come from?
Experts calculated the share of each of the five channels in the supply of the black market with illegal weapons.
In 2011, a report was prepared by the Centre for Problem Analysis and State Administration.
The experts analysed reports from the Ministry of the Interior and the Federal Service of State Statistics, criminal literature and publicly available data on arms portals.
According to the investigators, most of the illegal weapons come from the army and the legal protection authorities.
The report says that half of all weapons in the black market are there because of "the guilt of those responsible for their work with weapons."
According to the researchers, 17% of the weapons come from conflict areas, 14% come from arms production theft, and 5% come from illegal excavations.
A sales consultant of an arms store, who does not want to be called a name, assures that weapons found in illegal excavations have long since been out of date.
According to him, it is more common for traders to get the supplies in an arms camp.
