On that day, some Walmart employees, of whom there are 2.2 million worldwide, laid down their work and, together with trade unions and left-wing activists, spread branches of the chain, the target group of which are people of low and medium income.
Walmart sells all products, from diapers to hunting rifles and car batteries to vacuum cleaners, eggs and milk.
The product in the Walmart branches is on average between 8 and 27% cheaper than in large supermarkets.
Therefore, many of the low-paid Walmart employees only buy at their own workplace.
The prices and product range made Walmart one of the largest companies in the USA.
According to critics, Walmart can often only sell the goods so cheap because the employees are paid badly.
The latter also complain about heavy working conditions, such as missing forklifts or hand scanners.
The participants in the "Black Friday" protests called for wage increases and expressed their anger at the fact that the contribution to the company's health insurance had increased from 30 to 100 dollars a month.
A typical Walmart employee, who deserves 9.5 US dollars an hour, could not afford this increase, they said.
Researchers from the California University in Berkeley prove that if the company increased the average wage to 12 dollars an hour, it would cost Walmart 3.2 billion dollars.
This is about 1.1% more than they are now donating for pay.
If Walmart completely transferred the wage increases to the customers, each purchase cost them only 46 cents more in the future.
This would be an additional expenditure of only 12.39 dollars per year for them compared to today.
Proponents of Walmart are pleased to note that there have been protests in only nine states and that they did not bring any losses to the company.
The Black Friday lasted the next day in its store from 8: 00 in the evening on Thursday to midnight, and during this period Walmart sold about 5000 articles per second.
In total, the Walmart cash banks carried out almost 100 million transactions on "Black Friday."
The company's spokesperson, Dan Fogelman, in an interview on the website of the left-wing Huffington Post, claimed that "less than five" Walmart employees had completed the work and that the protest was only "another PR trick" of the union that organized the protests.
"Free cash!"
