Is there a similar authority to our NKτ here, or does the system work differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the German counterpart to the Federal Court of Auditors, which is similar to that of us and also has a college, which is only formed slightly differently, but in principle both authorities work in a similar way.
The competences are also to a certain extent comparable, but Germany is a state, that is to say, that there are these offices in the individual Länder - in this the German system is different from ours.
The BRH can only control federal funds, which is our state resources.
Public funds, which are managed by the districts and municipalities, are subject to the control of the national accounting offices.
As far as German legislation is concerned, is it easier than ours?
In general, I would hate to compare this without specific information. Nevertheless, in some respects, Germany is often referred to as a model, but it is certainly not possible to say that Germany is better in everything.
Is that perhaps because the examiners are better there?
I am sure not, but as I said, I do not like such comparisons.
It should also be noted that those countries that are a model for us also have problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have anything to do with our authority, would they?
As far as Czech legislation is concerned, what was the importance for your authority of the revision of the procurement law, do you already feel any impact?
In view of the fact that this amendment is only in force for a short time, it has not yet had an impact on our tests.
As our controls take place retrospectively, we have to expect a certain delay.
So far, we have had more impact in the preparation phase of future controls - we have introduced the new control instrument "Detection of risks of inefficiency" and have examined and analysed with this almost 14,000 public contracts - here, of course, the changes will have an impact as the thresholds, the conditions for certain types of tenders have been modified, including:
Do you see the adoption of this law rather positive, or is the system being burdened with further bureaucracy?
I think that this law is certainly a step in the right direction and I hope that this adoption will be confirmed.
However, the problem may arise that the rules become "stricter" and can no longer be respected.
Under the previous rules, the persons subject to an examination are already accountable to the institution (for example, in the case of an operational programme of regional policy, the Regional Council) to the effect that any non-compliance with the procurement law is equivalent to a breach of budgetary discipline.
But is it then useful to make the law even more stringent?
I do not think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack and abuse the system and not punish those who have committed a formal error that does not affect the actual decision-making process.
Such a system only puts the bureaucracy under even greater pressure.
Where's the way out?
Let us say first of all, which is not the way forward.
The Prime Minister recently said that the ODS would not be a problem for entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called "black system" - what exactly does that mean?
Is the black system now prohibited or allowed?
A law must be valid, and if something is prohibited by law, then it is not easy for the President of the Government to come and to hinder the control office whose duty is to control compliance with the law.
He can say, "We change the law and we allow it," but he can't say that we're pretending to be nothing.
The procurement law contains relatively strict rules on the formal execution of certain operations - and that is also right for the protection of public competition.
On the other hand, it is also tragic if the tenderer with the best offer is excluded only due to formal errors.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly - and that is what I think we are missing.
