Šimon Ornest: We want to collect positive energy on our concerts
What do you think about the end of the world in less than a month?
This is one of those disaster reports we people like to start on.
With our band The Tap Tap we make fun of it and say that we are the only band in the world that can collect enough positive energy to stop or prevent the end of the world.
In December you will also realize a unique project with three concerts against the end of the world.
Can you introduce the project to our readers?
This is a country-wide benefit event that we have been planning for two years.
To this end, we want to use the marketing potential of the Maya calendar, the end of which is forecast for December 21 at 11: 10 in the morning.
The day before, i.e. on December 20, three concerts will be held at the same time in Prague, Brno and Ostrava from 9: 00.
The end of the concerts is to be about the time that the Mayan calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which is in a time zone about 12 hours ahead of us.
Who did this idea come from?
Originally of me, then we developed the idea together with our graphic artist Honza Augusta.
In doing so, we would not only like to collect enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we would also like to think together with the public about the state in which we once hand this world over to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the Maya calendar, we have also developed a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and key holders against the end of the world, with which people can also support us via www.e-tap.cz.
The band The Tap Tap also recorded the so-called hymn against the end of the world with the title "The end of the world" together with other performers.
Already today the hymn on YouTube is very popular. Will it also sound at the benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, provided that everything works out and that the end of the world does not take place...
The hymn is to be sung at the same time by all the performers on all three concerts.
In addition, the hymns are broadcast live by Czech television in a direct connection.
The text of the hymn comes from Tomáš Hanák, who also plays the main character of Jesus in the video clip, also Xindl X sings with...
How did you get to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, which is related to the fact that we realize many benefit events and concerts...
We are trying to involve these people in our projects.
It has been shown that most people are interested in working with us and have fun with it.
What is the purpose of the proceeds of the concerts against the end of the world?
For the establishment of the barrier-free education centre Studeo, in which we have been working for six years together with the association Tap at the Jedlička Institute.
The students of the Jedlička Institute are regularly supported by lecturers who help them with different leisure activities.
Since the students themselves do not have the means to visit the lecturers, we would like to help them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building is to be created, to which we will then move in with this project.
There are several groups and performers at each concert.
What criteria did you choose them for?
We wanted to put together a program that would address all generations, including children.
In Prague, for example, there are Chinaski, support of Lesbians, illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý.
You can find out more on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are similar "major events" planned for the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, and for this concert we will also prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would also like to be in the Czech House in New York, and I would like to be personally - if we are in the United States - to be able to combine this with performances in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not very small, so far you have been in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage these trips in a logistical and organisational way?
It's not as bad as it seems at first sight.
Five of our members are wheelchair users, i.e. the wheelchairs must be transported in the luggage compartment. Furthermore, of course, we have to carry many instrument cases and other luggage...
Nevertheless, it has always worked without any problems so far, ČSA and British Airways have always been very well prepared for us, that sometimes I have already wondered.
Even in Moscow, where we were recently, there were no problems.
Through your travel abroad you have a comparison of how it looks like in the individual countries with accessibility, how to deal with disabled people, etc.
How have you experienced these things so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other cities where everything works better than we do with us, we were just in Russia witnessing that everything is still in its beginnings in the East.
In contrast to Prague, Moscow is absolutely not suitable for disabled people. It is still unusual there when someone is in a wheelchair alone in the city centre.
It is not even a matter of course there that you let a wheelchair driver in the elevator, for example.
Fortunately, there are also associations that try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what way do we have to catch up with the more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we're after...
It should be noted, however, that an improvement in the situation is still dependent on the efforts of those concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is absolutely common for people with serious disabilities to move independently in public space, to go to the museum, to use toilets, etc.
But it is not very common for a larger group of disabled people to be actively involved in the social events there, in which we are a little ahead of the West with the band The Tap Tap!
Respect in the public and accessibility is one thing, but only when important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers come out of our ranks will things really start to change.
So far, these are only individual cases of particularly strong-willed personalities.
The Tap Tap is very popular at the moment, but if we go back a few years, what motivated you to start a band in 1998?
At that time, I started as a maintainer at the Jedlička Institute, where I met a lot of young people who were interested in getting involved in something intense.
And since I am a musician and play saxophone, among other things, I founded a music company together with a colleague.
And over time, as our moderator, Láďa Angelovič, used to say, something has come out of control (laughs).
But the band only became known in the last few years, or am I wrong?
It is true that the cooperation with well-known singers has helped us; we have also started to actively promote ourselves.
We have become aware that if one does something and does not see it outside, one's performance in a certain sense does not exist.
Thanks to the EU funding, we can also afford good readers, high-quality equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to get it this far with The Tap Tap?
From the very beginning, I have felt the potential that things can be addressed differently.
In show business, one often copies the other.
This is logical in its own way, since everything new is considered with caution and only accepted after a long time.
There are only a few really unique things, and I dare to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression the viewer has most of the time is, of course, pity; this is only natural...
But this pity is absolutely unnecessary because people with disabilities are not lonely and abandoned beings that we must regret.
They are people who can live and develop a full life, provided they have the necessary means to do so.
I always say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is not only progress for themselves, but for the whole of society.
Was it also helpful for this success that you are a strict boss, as you can hear from many people?
If you want to do something good, you cannot compromise in many things and you must also call for a certain discipline.
I think, however, that is quite normal.
Some come to us with romantic ideas, and when they find that they have rehearsal twice a week, have to complete preparatory phases and spend a lot of time on concert trips, then the enthusiasm of many quickly disappears.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every band that wants to work seriously and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many of them have been present since the beginning, i.e. since 1998?
Just one: Láďa Angelovič.
We're an open group, people come and go.
Who has the will and the desire to participate is always welcome with us.
