Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the Space Agency at a meeting of the Council of Ministers of the European Space Agency's member countries, the second member of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and in the following years took part in several ESA projects.
The path of Poland to space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos were concerned with space, with which they did not always have an understanding.
I would like to remind you of the presentation by A. Šternfeld of 6 December 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entrance to Cosmonautics."
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, donated by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch for "Entrance to the Cosmonautics."
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognised contribution to the development of space was, among other things, appreciated by the name of one of the craters on the ground side of the moon after him.
As early as 1925, a railway-Draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project were unfortunately not known.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used to start or brake the dragons.
The information on this is from the contemporary press only.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered bullets.
The research was carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
It can be seen from the documents that the research had advanced to the stage of practical testing.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937 the technical press of the design of a photo-electric hunting dragon by Ing. Rohzoński showed up, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda poweitrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects were concerned with the military use of the rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy).
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of work its work was completed from the beginning of the war.
Other articles on space were published in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company is made in 1954 in the November issue of the magazine Problem, in which four extensive articles are devoted to space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to set up a space society.
At the time, there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be expected that the exploration of space would have a future.
As early as its beginnings in 1956, the Polish space company PTA made an effort to join the International Federation for Space, founded in 1951, and in fact the PTA became a full member in the autumn of 1956.
The following year, the first PTA president, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959), was Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has played a major role in the development of the highly successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first started on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and weighed not entirely 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 in the Błędów desert, flight tests began with the two-stage RM-2.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach a height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of high-speed winches.
In 1962, however, the further development was stopped.
The first RM-type missile was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the starting weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this rocket were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which were different in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B over 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C over 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight height for all three types was 37 km.
In the years 1965 to 1968 the Meteor-2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning the accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, followed by the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
