In November 1979, a mob of demonstrating Islamist students occupied the US Embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats as hostages.
For their release, they called for the delivery of the fallen Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who had fled to the United States after the revolution, who had kept the patronage of his regime for decades.
There was no positive way out of this situation for the American government - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as this would have severely damaged the confidence of its allies in other countries.
At the same time, it was unable to enforce the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a serious blow to the call of the united states, and the subsequent fiasco in the violent attempt to release the hostages made everything worse.
The diplomats who were captured were finally released after 444 days after negotiations had been mediated by the Algerian government.
The fate of the hostages at home created a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian moods.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo of the director and actor Ben Affleck describes an episode of this story that gave the US a small partial victory.
Just before the occupation of the embassy, six embassy staff were able to escape.
This ended after numerous complications in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to bring the refugees from Iran, helping them with an extravagant story to cover their true identity - they travelled with Canadian passports as members of a film staff who allegedly visited locations in the country for a science fiction film.
Combination of the genres
The plan developed by the Exfiltration expert, Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the cover credible, articles about this film project appeared in professional journals, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of this operation have been kept secret for a long time. The film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck's film is a special combination of several film genres.
On the one hand, he is a realistic political thriller, but at the same time also a so-called "Caper Movie," that is, the story of a successful humour-piece, such as the film Ocean's Eleven.
As a result, the levels of mood change in the film - on the one hand, the documentary scenes from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic contemporary photographs are shown, and also in the film version of the same situations there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the looser passages from Hollywood, which come ironic and slightly overpointed.
And then there are the scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits at the meeting table, on the corridors, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has made a remarkable reboot of his career with this film.
A smiling actor has become a respectable director, and as an actor he is no longer the goal of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film after the Crimean No Children's Play (Gone Baby Gone, 2007) and the Thriller City without Grace (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film, which does not play in the director's home Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of the place was one of the features that removed the previous films of this director from the standard Hollywood.
Affleck, however, also proves this feeling in Argo, where Tehran is "played" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film play in the streets and show the reconstruction of events that really took place - the entry sequence of the storming of the message is very impressive in its clarity, yet it still conveys the feeling of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere.
A similar effect is achieved by Affleck with his team in fictional scenes (the wrong film stick on a bazaar in Tehran).
Too much action in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story does not actually offer many exciting scenes in the film sense.
But with the few, he works quite successfully, sometimes helping the reality a little - which does not always seem so elegant (the scenes in which the threatening crisis at the airport in Tehran is averted by a telephone call in America, or even the persecution on the runway, seem somewhat artificial).
The weakness of Argo is its too wide spread, which is due to the need to show too much of action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in their roles as Hollywood employees, but their characters deserve more space, and they are far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film is thus losing some of the pull force. It is a film that you can track with some interest, while gouging the design and the retro-style reminiscent of a thriller from the 70's.
However, it is difficult for him to arouse enthusiasm.
However, as a reminder of a piece of history that is still alive in a certain way and as a proof of how excessive the ideas of the omnipotent and all-knowing secret services are, it is sufficient.
