The prosecutor's office tried on Friday to establish that the army-run Bradley Manning - accused of the greatest disclosure of confidential information in US history - failed to complain about the alleged abuse in military custody.
In a cross-examination of Manning during a pre-trial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Maj. Ashden Fein explained that documents on weekly visits to prison officials during Manning's nine-month detention period in Quantico, Virginia did not have any complaints about his treatment.
One day before the cross-examination, which was held as a result of a request by the defense to dismiss the charge - Manning had already been punished enough by the hard detention period - Manning had declared that he had considered the suicide in prison.
The US Army intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The material was then released by WikiLeaks on the Internet.
WikiLeaks never confirmed Manning as the source of the information.
In the hearing on Friday, Fein and Manning went through the forms that officials had filled in after their meetings with Manning during his detention in the Quantico military prison, where he had been in increased detention conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officials asked Manning questions and wrote down his answers.
When Fein asked him about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he had considered the treatment by his guards as "excellent" and the treatment by the institution as a whole as "very professional."
The forms, said Fein, did not contain any complaints about abuse, even though the officials had asked Manning directly for his treatment.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally and that the officials had discussed them with him and indicated that they should deal with them, but they had not been recorded.
"They wrote (after discussion of the concerns)" No problems, "and that did not necessarily mean that I said nothing at all," said Manning.
The judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment when he met with a committee in January 2011 to examine the suicidal thoughts he mentioned on a form a few months before.
Manning replied that his intention during this meeting was to lower his observation status for "prevention of injuries."
The military said it assigned this restrictive status - one level under the risk of suicide - to him and to the protection of others.
"I wanted to convince employees that I was well and to get rid of the observation status to prevent injuries (...) in order to achieve a higher quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
On Thursday, Manning announced his arrest and transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for about two months before being transferred to the Quantico Marines Prison in Virginia in July 2010.
He said he had considered the suicide in Kuwait and had become unconscious because of the heat.
Not to be allowed to know what was happening to him or in the outside world was burdensome.
"My world shrunk on Camp Arafjon, on this cage together," said Manning on Thursday.
I thought I was gonna die in that cage.
When he was moved to Quantico, Manning spent most of his days in a small cell - at least 21 hours and often more than 23 hours - and without company.
He was only allowed a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, clothes and his glasses.
Manning said he was trying to keep moving, because on the day it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down.
He always had to sleep with light that came into his cell from the outside.
When he turned around at night and guards couldn't see his face, they woke him up to turn back.
In January 2011, Manning's lawyer formally objected to the treatment of Manning.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
On Friday, the judge also asked Manning about an accusation he had raised in his statement on Thursday - so he had to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night and stand naked in front of guards and other prisoners in a morning count.
Manning had said that he had never had the opportunity to cover himself with his ceiling during this count.
At the Friday interview, Manning said that he had closed a command from his guard that he should have dropped the ceiling with which he could have covered himself. However, he admitted that no one had asked him to do so.
On Thursday, Manning had testified that he was forced to sleep naked the previous night. He had previously tried to show an official that he was no danger to himself.
Manning told the official that he could have used the covenant of his underpants or his flip-flops to hurt himself, but did not.
That night, Manning said, his underpants, flip-flops and glasses were removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that the judge will at least take into account his detention experiences and reduce his level of detention drastically if he is to be sentenced to the military court at his trial, which is scheduled for the beginning of next year.
The defense has stated that Manning will claim guilty of lower crimes, while other charges, which are considered too extreme, will be challenged.
The hearing is scheduled to continue this weekend, and the public prosecutor is expected to justify the conditions of arrest.
The Pentagon remains in its position that Manning has been held in accordance with the rules applicable to all prisoners held under the highest security arrangements in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include the benefit of the enemy, the illegal publication of secret information on the Internet, the transfer of national defence information and the theft of public property or documents.
If he is found guilty on all counts, he is in danger of a life sentence.
