For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano put their lives and health at risk if they carry 70 kilos of sulphur over the steep, rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others work literally in hell.
This is the case with Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 mine workers who earn their lives by bringing sulphur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To this end, he must rise every day down to the ground of his crater, where the gas from the earth is in contact with the air.
After breaking out large sulfur stones, which can weigh up to 70 kg in total, he transports them in two bamboo baskets on his shoulders over the sloping paths of stone.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to a height of 2386 meters, but the exhausted carriers need more than 40 minutes for the ascent in the turtle's tempo, while they have to keep the balance and take their steps carefully so that they do not slip and crash.
They know that every step can cost their lives as it happened to a French tourist who crashed years ago on the steep slopes of the Kawah Ijen.
The mining workers of Kawah Ijen deserve 5 Eurocent for each kilo of sulphur they're cutting.
