The company is PT Candi Ngrimbi, who since 1960 has taken advantage of the deposits in the volcano and (never better said) its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocent) for each kilo of sulphur.
This is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocent) to the petrochemical industry, because this mineral is widely used in everyday life and is used for the production of matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even for the bleaching of sugar.
"As we usually wear 70 kg, we get about 46.000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each way," explains Anto, who usually makes three routes a day.
For each route it takes three hours, after which it is completely completed, but at the end of the day it has 138,000 rupees (11.5 Euro) together.
What looks like a miserable reward for such a seemingly inhumane effort is, however, the triple of what he would earn with the field work.
"The daily wage of the mine workers here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly income is two million rupees (167 euros), is very high," explains the carrier who previously worked as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There he earned 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the work was not so hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village nearby, and for a reason that is as important as the sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali where they are Hinduists, and I brought her to Java to convert her to Islam."
