But Lim Yew Soon, Director General of the real estate company EL Developers, says that his "shoe boxes" can be sold much faster than larger housing units.
They are so popular and the units are sold out by days and even weeks faster than the larger housing units.
This means that they are much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new standards give the developers clearer guidelines, which were previously put in the way of obstacles if they wanted to build too many small housing units within a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
Even if these new rules could pave the way for an increase in the national birth rate, the discussions with the Singapore people working in the financial district will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, the apartments and also the education are expensive, so it is pushed away by many," says a young manager.
The children can have others.
"It is important for me to have my own money and time," says another man, about twenty years old.
Men and women are leading their careers, the stress and the cost of property and education as reasons for not having children.
That is why the Singapore people have the last word when it comes to having children - so much can be done by the government.
The offline private offline is online private
Privacy
According to the dictionary, this is the property of private or "the area of private life where you are entitled to protection from any kind of interference."
What's private for someone under 16?
How is this definition applied to its everyday life and the social networks?
Does he understand the dangers he faces when he makes known on the Internet situations that he would not share in real life?
El Periódico interviewed five young people between the ages of 10 and 15, who are often on the net.
In four of the cases, they linked the term "something very own" to the personal level and "to the password and the user" when applying it to the social networks.
"I would not announce my deepest secrets in a post," says the 10-year-old Jorge in trying to explain the meaning of "private" in websites such as Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very confidential secrets, my mother is allowed to know them, but not the whole world," he confirms.
On FB I upload beautiful pictures or pictures of games.
I'm wasting my time with friends, too.
"I would not share a photo that is not of me, or of someone who makes the fool," he says.
The boy is aware that it is wrong to publish obscene photos, of naked, of crimes, or to write offensive or violent comments.
Jorge assures to know 35 friends he has in FB and nine followers in Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Among them is the mother who has the password to one of the accounts.
I signed up to Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if anyone answers me, I just upload them," he adds.
"The social networks are entertaining, I can quickly talk to relatives in the distance or with friends" he says.
In question, he answers that he would never accept an invitation from an unknown.
Even if someone saw a stranger, he would ignore it.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
The teenager has user accounts in Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask. In Ask he admits to not know 20 of the people he added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me because we have something in common, for example music," he says.
According to the boy, no one told him or asked him for his address or phone number.
"If someone is pushing me or asking me to do it, I will just remove it from my user account" he admits.
José contacted Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy's experience is not unknown, which is known today as cyberbullying.
A friend's acquaintance was blackmailed in a social network.
They threatened him and asked for money.
"He never knew who it was," he assures.
According to José, the victim has not closed the user account.
"He only made it private."
Then he explains a number of steps to configure a user account safely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yeah, I'd do that if he was unsympathetic to me or I wanted to wipe one out of him.
"But I know this is cyberbullying," he explains.
Key issues
Marielos Porras, a teacher of English with a degree in education and learning, believes that in order to guide the children and young people, it is necessary to understand that it is the purpose of the social networks to inform.
"The Internet was created as a medium for the search for information, but with the appearance of these pages the rules of the game have changed," she says.
Porras explains that the academic Marc Prensky, holder of a master's title in pedagogy at the University of Yale and author of the work "Digital Natives and Immigrants," formed these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who grew up with this technology.
"We are the digital immigrants they are supposed to teach, while we are still learning," he says.
He explained that this is a complex issue, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion on what can be disseminated, published or said, and at an age where the maturity is not sufficient."
"They should also be picky when it is most important for them to be popular, to have thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences," he adds.
According to the expert, the most effective way to teach children and young people what privacy is to ask them questions that make them think.
"To tell them not to do it doesn't work," he says.
Porras then calls some possibilities: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger. Then why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like to be published a photo of you, like the one you published from a friend?
Do you know what the others are doing about you?
Did you ask the other people for permission first when you tagged photos of parties?
And one more question: do everyone need to know what you're doing at any moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they have to act online, as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
"Someone outside the Internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, and the same must apply to social networks," he explains.
Monitoring
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, comments that it is essential that parents read the guidelines of social networks carefully.
If they understand all the sections, they have solid foundations to talk to their children about the importance of opening a user account on the Internet.
"For example, age, or what you can share or publish," he explains.
According to Guardia, the children must be reminded of the lesson "You should not speak to strangers."
Closure of the Unasu Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (Unasu) ended today in Peru without publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and was to be signed theoretically by the seven governors present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of the Unasu. Sources in the State and President's Office at the beginning indicated that they would be handed it over after the examination, but then stated that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government's website.
When asked about the text, they said that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
The access of journalists to information on the summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only the image of the president meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the message "private session, limited audio."
The few information that was circulating among the journalists was received by the press speakers of some of the Unasu governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was published during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from different national and international media who called for more information.
After that, the President of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "Final Declaration" of the Summit, but it was the Humala Declaration and not the official document at the end of the Summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite a strong press call, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced before, was not published.
On the official website of the ASSPA you can see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed the existence of information systems for journalists, but to a large extent they limited access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Court of Justice of The Hague, which settled a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which starts on Monday in The Hague, in the process that Lima initiated against Santiago, to listen to the requests of both sides.
"We will follow and implement the judgment on the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," said Humala, together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is, and remains, a country that is in keeping with international laws, seeking peaceful solutions to disputes, concluding agreements and submitting to the international courts," adds Piñera and greeted Humala with a hand-pressure in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the IGH was made after Colombia had brought an action against the Bogotá Agreement, following a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered to be a serious mistake, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasu since 2011 after the resignation of its President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit in Lima shortly after the midday.
The head of state read the final document, in which it announced that 16 decisions were taken and that the lines of action for 31 projects between the South American countries were set for a total investment of $17 billion.
On the decisions taken, he said that the countries of the Unasu will "take important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, to which we will extend the decisions on residence rights."
It announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised transnational crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act together and efficiently in the event of natural disasters."
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant trains, but should serve to expand our production performance and show our peoples a better future," added Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects designed to improve the territorial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and open up new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a read-out statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvian, which were on the cross-sections of its area from the coast to Brazil, and two of which should provide a better connection with Ecuador, even though it did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the election process in this country will be used for its resumption in the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourly relations was another aspect that was stressed at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before the beginning of his participation in the regional meeting, that he expected a meeting in Mexico on Saturday with his opponent of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect for an IGH judgment called into question by Bogotá.
"Maybe I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday)," said Santos.
"We will all look at these ways - they are not excluded, and the agreement with Nicaragua also requires talks with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we will deal with this matter as civilized and respectful as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet on Saturday in Mexico, where they intend to be present at the take-up of the new President of the country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
As part of the summit, the defence ministers of the block for the adoption of the 2013 action plan also met in advance, in order to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defence of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Surinam and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, even if the latter country is currently excluded.
Peru is the president of the regional block.
