The reason for dying because of AIDS is now too late to recognize
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the results of the investigation: HIV-positive.
"It was as if a bomb had hit," he says about the moment he received the diagnosis that the doctor "tried to weaken" without any apparent success.
He hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his disease alone and began to find out about it; and this with such commitment that he was just celebrating his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV unit of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), in which he came after several fights in 1994.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, which was difficult to imagine in the early 1990s when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigmata.
At that time, the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye, "because it led to a dead end."
At that time, AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today it is possible to survive this syndrome also with quality of life.
However, many people still come to the hospital who know nothing about their disease and who have already done damage to the virus and have exhausted their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the appearance of AIDS in the world, that is, after the first reported cases, "today's great success means that the survival of a patient taking up treatment in time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same," said the head of the HIV unit of the HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, saying that this information was supported by a respected scientific publication in April this year.
The expert on infectious diseases and HIV / AIDS, Andrade Villanueva, commented that the scientists concluded since 2008 that AIDS was not a death sentence, but that the years of survival and quality of life depended on the degree of impairment of the immune system of people at the beginning of treatment, and that those who are not drug-dependent would have greater chances: up to 30 years with a count of 200 CD4 and 50 years with a count of 500 CD4.
Simply put, the above statements mean that those who receive the HIV-positive diagnosis at the age of 25 can in this sense "easily become 75 years old as long as they are under control," said this expert.
In order to be able to properly classify this progress, it must be recalled that the life expectancy of the Mexicans today is on average 76 years.
Even if mortality has decreased significantly in recent years (in Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has decreased from 6,678 cases in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (ONUSIDA annual report), it is true that 60% of patients in the national database have died since the appearance of AIDS.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and by May of this year there are 187 deaths, but it is assured that there has been universal access to the antiretroviral medicines since 2005.
So why are people still dying of it?
In my opinion, the problem is not access to treatment.
This is my opinion, and that's what's in our hospital.
At least in the past 12 years we have had no supply problems with the drugs. The problem is that the people come in a very advanced state because they do not know their state of infection, that is, in very late stages of the disease.
He makes a striking statement: "Nine out of ten patients come to us if they already have an accompanying infection. In order to be able to influence global mortality, more early diagnoses are required, which is why it is necessary to offer massive recognition tests to all those who need it."
This proposal is accepted by the experts and officials of the Consejo Estatal de Prevención del Sida en Jalisco (Coesida) (State Committee on Aids Prevention in Jalisco) and also by the patients like Fabrizio, who had his test carried out in a private laboratory, for the only reason that it had made a friend of him who, despite his young age, was already in the AIDS phase and even had the Kaposi sarcoma (a cancer-like tumor), which is one of the usual complications.
Everything's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they're going to die, and they don't want to hear anything.
"If I have to die, I'd rather burst three times," they say in my case.
The change was for improvement, I feed well, drive sports and take the drugs.
All his parents know today is that he had cancer.
I live a normal life, like everyone else.
"I work, do a lot, have an active but responsible sex life, I pay attention to my health and that of the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimate details with MILENIO JALISCO in order to animate those who are afraid today in the context of the world's AIDS day.
They should take the test if they are part of the risk group. The sooner they know if they are HIV-positive, the better, and if they already know the diagnosis, they should learn how to live responsibly like all people.
His message is a summary of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms behind the shop table
There are large holes between the health programmes and the ordinary citizen, explains Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara, who has taken up the cause of HIV.
And the most important thing is prevention.
The distribution of condoms has actually been increased in the places in which it is intended; in the past they have been delivered individually, now they give us packages of a hundred pieces, which is already good, but there are still people who do not have access to a condom, "he said.
The young people are at risk of new infections.
"What do you need it for?" is a common mockery of social workers, guidance staff in schools, in pharmacies and in the health system, which does not want to be exposed to young people, the correspondent assured.
He proposed to reorient this inefficient distribution; the condoms should not only be behind the shop table, but in public toilets of facilities often visited by young people.
It is not intended to promote democracy.
They are not to be paid for the beer and motel, as the governor Emilio González answered the question of whether the Preservatives would be distributed under his administration.
"Sexuality does not look like this; it is best to bring the condoms closer to those who are already engaged in sexual activity," he put it to the point.
Key data of Jalisco
There are 13,435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is in the fourth place of new and combined AIDS cases, and in the 13th place of HIV.
92% of cases of infection are caused by sexual intercourse, 6% by blood and 2% by perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people live with HIV because there are 4 or 5 people who do not know for each registered case.
