Larry Hagman was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas and became famous worldwide with his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as "J.R." in the television series "Dallas," where he played a ruthless, insidious and manipulating businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as the oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of the greed of the 1980s, is dead.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas," died Friday afternoon due to cancer complications according to a press release from the family at The Associated Press by Warner Bros., producer of "Dallas."
"Larry was back in his beloved birth town of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he liked most," said the family.
The family of Larry and his closest friends were with him in Dallas for the celebration of the Thanksgiving.
Linda Gray, who played the role of his wife in the original and follow-up series, was with Hagman when he died in the Dallas hospital, her publicist Jeffrey Lane said.
He made everyone who knew him happy.
He was creative, generous, funny, funny, loving and talented, and I'm going to miss him very much.
"He was an original person and lived life in full," Gray said in a message.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis in 1992, and he admitted that he had been drinking a lot for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found in his liver and he was undergoing a transplant.
In the years before "Dallas," Hagman was known on television as a nice type in 1965-1970 with the sitcom "Enchanting Jeannie" of the television station NBC.
There he played the astronaut Tony Nelson, whose life is turned upside down when he meets an attractive "jinn" (played by Barbara Eden), who will live with him at home.
He was also the actor of two comedies, which were only broadcast for a short time, such as The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film works included well-rated roles in "The Group," "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors."
But it was his masterful interpretation of the enchanting J.R. that made Hagman a superstar.
The dramatic series of the CBS television chain about the Ewing-Clan and other figures in their area was broadcast from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising claim "Who shot at J.R.?," which was intended to create expectation for an episode of emotions where the figure of Hagmann was almost killed, led to an international speculation, and millions of dollars were bet in competitions.
The series then reached a record of the audience at that time.
When the answer was known in a chapter in November 1990, it was seen by an average of 41 million spectators who turned "Dallas" into the second most-seen entertainment programme since the end of "MASH" in 1983, which had 50 million spectators.
It was Kristin who had shot the sister-in-law of J.R. (interpreted by Mary Crosby).
J.R. had made her pregnant and threatened to present her as a prostitute if she did not leave the city, but others also had reasons to want him dead.
Hagman interpreted the role of Ewing as a corrupt, insatiable man with a charismatic smile: a hideous businessman and unfaithful husband who sought to have his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) appointed.
"I know what to say on J.R. 's tombstone," Hagman said in 1988.
It should be called "Here rests the honourable citizen J.R. Ewing."
This is the only business he didn't win.
Victoria Principal, co-actress of the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as an "enormous personality on and outside the screen."
